    {
      "date": "2026-06-26",
      "label": "Partly re-add memory after Micron's blowout; keep Broadcom on Jalape\u00f1o",
      "rationale": "Two weeks ago I trimmed the memory/HBM names hard, and the thesis has only gotten stronger, so I'm partially re-adding. On June 24 Micron reported a record quarter and guided FQ4 to ~$50B revenue, ~86% gross margin and ~$31 EPS, with HBM sold out through 2026 and HBM4 ramping twice as fast as HBM3E; SK Hynix is similarly sold out, and DRAM ASPs are inflecting up sharply as capacity tilts to HBM. I'm lifting MU to 7.5% and SK Hynix to 6.5% (the cleanest sold-out plays), with MRVL to 6.0% and STX to 5.0% \u2014 still well below where they'd sit on price alone, but no longer fighting a confirmed structural shortage. Funding comes from shaving the stretched equipment/data-centre winners (ASML, EQIX, TSM, ANET each to ~6.5-7.0%) and from cash, which drops to ~5.5%. I'm keeping Broadcom as the single biggest weight at 8.5% after the June 24 OpenAI 'Jalape\u00f1o' custom-inference-chip reveal and reiterated >$100B AI-semi guidance \u2014 it's still only +9% YTD, the cheapest growth in the book. CEG held at 7.0%: it signed a Walmart nuclear PPA and screens cheap vs a ~$360 median target, but it's been the lone loser two weeks running so I'm not adding more. All 15 names stay in; weights sum to 0.945 with the rest in cash.",
