    {
      "date": "2026-07-02",
      "label": "Hold the memory line, keep Broadcom on top, add to the CEG laggard",
      "rationale": "July-4 observed holiday means markets are shut Friday, so I'm dating this to Thursday 2026-07-02. The book is now +90.7% active vs the S&P's +9.1%, and the memory/HBM thesis has if anything strengthened: on July 2 TrendForce reported SK Hynix is removing the price cap in its long-term agreements so contract prices can fully track a tightening spot market (Micron kept a cap at Q2-2026 levels), and server-DRAM demand is guided up ~60% into 2027. But MU (+209%), SK Hynix (+201%), STX (+186%) and MRVL (+175%) are already the most stretched names in the book, and a ~June-25 antitrust suit alleging a coordinated HBM-driven DDR3/DDR4 curtailment adds headline/legal risk \u2014 so I'm holding these four steady at last week's 7.5/6.5/5.0/6.0 rather than chasing them higher: participate in the shortage, don't press it. Broadcom stays the single largest weight at 8.5%: after the June-24 OpenAI 'Jalape\u00f1o' reveal (1.3GW in 2027, part of a 10GW deal through 2029) it has actually cheapened to just +4% YTD \u2014 still the cheapest growth in the book. The one change of conviction is Constellation: it's the lone loser at -34.5% after a June $3.1B secondary, but the nuclear-for-AI story is intact (reaffirmed $11-12 EPS, ~$360 median target), so I'm lifting CEG from 7.0% to 7.5% funded by trimming stretched winner AMAT (+125%) from 6.0% to 5.5%. Equipment (TSMC $52-56B capex, ASML raised + \u20ac12B buyback, AMAT equipment +30%) and networking (Arista FY26 ~$11.5B) all remain healthy but already-run, so I leave them put. All 15 names stay in; weights sum to 0.945 with ~5.5% cash.",
